Because borrowing from Peter to pay Tom cannot be sustained, we have been pushed back into the era of debilitating Structural Adjustment Programmes (SAPs). SAPs were extremely devastating because of retrenchment in public service and cost-sharing in access to government services, which sprouted corruption. The county is now painfully renegotiating how to reschedule is debts lest it defaults.
This comes with extremely penalising demands for government — to make budget cuts by retrenching workers, and raising taxes. Already, about 70,000 public servants are targeted.
Conditions to access World Bank and IMF loans are already manifesting in removal of tax reductions extended as stimulus mitigation against Covid-19. VAT is back to its maximum 16 per cent, with a consequent rise in unaffordable prices of basic consumer goods.
High taxes
Just to demonstrate how hamstrung the government is, new high taxes are being applied to already impoverished and reduced tax base due to job losses and many business closures.
Though no indication yet on where government will apply budget cuts, the loans-guzzling mega edifices appear safe, magnified by increased gusto to showcase transport infrastructure projects.



