Meanwhile, government is struggling to meet monthly wage commitments. Disbursements to county governments are lagging behind. Promises to refurbish schools for Covid-19-free reopening in January are just that, promises. Picketing health workers’ demands for basic safety measures against Covid-19 are dismissed.
National security threat
Ironically, Kenya puts a premium on education, but has shortage of teachers, while thousands of their trained ranks are unemployed. And government threatens to sack health workers in the midst of a pandemic and implementation of UHC. Desperation leading to increase in taxes is understandable.
But does government know it is taxing equally desperate, poor and sick people? People are sick and unproductive because they don’t have jobs and cannot get treated in hospitals.
Before, good counsel prevailed; arrogance, threats and intimidation did not get patients admitted to hospitals since government had refused to talk staff welfare.



