A paralysed heath system is a national security threat. Recent government inactions and actions abet Covid-19 spread and infections. Austerity measures should not immobilise key sectors of agriculture, manufacturing, health, education and social support schemes.
While politicians have their diaries marked out for 2021, most Kenyans are staring at a void after losing their livelihoods in 2020.
Covid-19 is unrelenting as fatigue competes with anti-Covid-19 rules. I plead with fellow Kenyans not to relax in protecting themselves against Covid-19. Protecting oneself can’t be enforced; it is self-discipline.
Vaccines may be on the way, but will not be useful to those already Covid-19 positive. Despite empty pockets, wear a mask, wash hands, keep your distance. Avoid crowded places to which politicians are likely to draw you without protection. Jubilee and OMD have submitted names to the IEBC amid talks of cooperation. Impeached Waititu and exiled Miguna are also in the contest. They have joined nurses and clinicians in their strike, a decision that will further paralyse services in public hospitals. A six-tonne consignment of drugs wasted away at the airport for three years because government officials differed over its clearance.